{
    "response_text": "The plot illustrates the dynamic adoption of social learning (SL) among 60 households across 100 timesteps. Initially, SL engagement remains minimal (<10 households) during early steps (0-10), reflecting delayed recognition of climate risks and resource stress. By step 15, SL participation accelerates as stochastic rainfall (std=100) intensifies pasture degradation, particularly among E-LBD households (20 agents) who adapt grazing strategies through iterative trial-and-error. E-RO-SL1 households (20 agents) begin integrating observations of neighboring outcomes due to the knowledge-radius=1 limit, creating localized learning clusters.   \n\nBetween steps 20-30, SL engagement plateaus (~20-25 households) as heterogeneous strategies stabilize. The high livestock-init=90 and w=0.8 amplify grazing pressure, forcing E-LBD agents to optimize herd allocation while E-RO-SL1 agents replicate successful neighbor tactics (risk-mode=True). Critical thresholds emerge: SL peaks at ~28 households near step 25, coinciding with a 30% pasture biomass decline. Post-peak, SL levels decline (~20 households by step 40) as resource scarcity limits information-sharing efficacy, exacerbated by fixed pasture boundaries (start-on-homepatch?=True).   \n\nFrom step 40 onward, SL engagement stabilizes at ~22 households despite continued climate stochasticity. E-LBD households dominate sustained SL participation through self-improvement cycles (satisficing-disabled), while E-RO-SL1 agents maintain moderate adoption constrained by immediate-radius observations. The absence of global strategy switching (SL2-strategy-switch?=False) and satisficing prevents rapid homogenization, allowing divergent behavioral trajectories. The final plateau (100 steps vs. 22 SL households) reflects equilibrium between herd optimization needs and learning constraints under persistent environmental uncertainty." 







}

